4 November 1430","1339–1420":"1339–1420","1340–1386":"1340–1386","1345–1430":"1345–1430","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1349–1412":"1349–1412","1375–1447":"1375–1447","1314–1373":"1314–1373","1318–1350":"1318–1350","about 1370":"about 1370","1373":"1373","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","4 November 1430":"4 November 1430","before 1339":"before 1339","1349":"1349","1447":"1447","1314":"1314","1412":"1412","1345":"1345","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1386":"1386","1318":"1318","1339":"1339","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Hethersett, , Norfolk, England":"Hethersett, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bermingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam, Sinead.","Irish (of English origin): variant of   Birmingham  . This form of the surname is found mainly in Ireland.","History: The Bermingham family take their surname from lands held at what is now a great city in the West Midlands of England, but it was brought to Ireland as early as the 12th century. The Norman baron Robert de Bermyngeham was a follower of Strongbow (see   Clare  ); his name is found on a number of Irish charters between 1175 and 1179. The family was also known as <i>Mac Fheorais</i> (see   Corish  ) in Ireland, named for Piers (Gaelic <i>Feoras</i>) de Bermyngeham, the father of Robert."],"variants":[{"name":"Birmingham","meanings":["English: habitational name from Birmingham in the West Midlands. In Domesday Book the name is already found as <i>Bermingeham</i>, but it seems likely that it was originally <i>Beornmundingahām</i> ‘homestead (Old English <i>hām</i>) of the people of (<i>-inga-</i>) <i>Beornmund</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>beorn</i> ‘young man, warrior’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’. This surname is established in Ireland (see   Bermingham  )."]},{"name":"Corish","meanings":["Irish:","shortened form of <i>Mac Fheorais</i> ‘son of Piers’. The name was borne by a Connacht family descended from Piers de Bermingham, second lord of Athenry in Galway (died <i>c.</i> 1309). Compare   Bermingham  .","shortened form of <i>Mac Muirghis</i> ‘son of <i>Maurice</i>’, a personal name introduced to Ireland by the Normans. Compare   Morrissey  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Bermingham was born in 1345, in Birmingham, Warwickshire, England, his father, Fulk de Bermingham, was 31 and his mother, Joan, was 27. He married Isabel Whitacre about 1370, in Birmingham, Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 4 November 1430, in his hometown, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1345–4 November 1430":"1345–4. november 1430","1339–1420":"1339–1420","1340–1386":"1340–1386","1345–1430":